column36: Placed in Grade 3 hurdles last two starts; good form claims but others have more potential
column37: Has a wealth of experience with 37 runs under her belt; placed in Grade 3 hurdles on her last two starts, third at Navan (2m, soft/heavy) on latest; top on RPRs and should be thereabouts but others have more potential.

column32: Vincent Caldwell & Angela Shamoon & Mrs A Shamoon Ibgi
column36: Ended last season with Scottish National win, was effective over this trip as a hurdler
column37: Retains his novice status to this point in the season, reminiscent of the stable's 2023 winner I Am Maximus; ended last season with Scottish National win; was effective over this trip as a hurdler; could go well though Gold Dancer looks like the stable's main hope.

column20: 3/1 Ip Up, 4/1 Dinofromberlais,  Stardrop, 6/1 Close Combat,  He's A Latchico, 10/1 Activist, 14/1 Wewillgowithplanb,  Jiair Madrik, 50/1 Golden Move
column27: Scea De Maulepaire & M C De Saint Seine
column36: Three consecutive wins since May, form of Galway festival success has been well-advertised
column37: Expensive French recruit; failed to live up to price tag over hurdles and flopped on his only chase start last season; now paying his way with three consecutive wins since May; form of Galway festival success from stablemate Westport Cove has been well-advertised; straightforward task at Tipperary last time.

column20: 3/1 Ip Up, 4/1 Dinofromberlais,  Stardrop, 6/1 Close Combat,  He's A Latchico, 10/1 Activist, 14/1 Wewillgowithplanb,  Jiair Madrik, 50/1 Golden Move
column36: Has made an excellent transition to chasing with Galway and Cork wins, deserves a shot
column37: Progressive hurdler last season, ending up with a rating of 138; justified favouritism when landing a 2m2f beginners' chase in gutsy style at Galway on return to action, form boosted by runner-up Will The Wise; confirmed promise with Grade 3 win over 2m4f at Cork; deserves a shot at this.

column20: 3/1 Ip Up, 4/1 Dinofromberlais,  Stardrop, 6/1 Close Combat,  He's A Latchico, 10/1 Activist, 14/1 Wewillgowithplanb,  Jiair Madrik, 50/1 Golden Move
column32: Mrs M Roden & Mrs R Nolan
column36: Three chase wins in small-field events, well held by Gold Dancer on Tipperary running
column37: Smart hurdler in his early days; all three chase wins recorded in small-field events between April and June this year; failed to make the grade in Grade 3 events before livelier display at Cheltenham and in the Troytown; however, well held by Gold Dancer on Tipperary running.

column20: 3/1 Ip Up, 4/1 Dinofromberlais,  Stardrop, 6/1 Close Combat,  He's A Latchico, 10/1 Activist, 14/1 Wewillgowithplanb,  Jiair Madrik, 50/1 Golden Move
column36: Not far off the best of last term's novice hurdlers, good start over fences at Down Royal
column37: Point winner and course bumper winner; not far off the best of last term's novice hurdlers; won Grade 1 Leopardstown event at Christmas and better in defeat when placed at the same level at both Cheltenham and Aintree; made a good start over fences at Down Royal; leading chance for trainer who has won this race a record eight times.

column20: 3/1 Ip Up, 4/1 Dinofromberlais,  Stardrop, 6/1 Close Combat,  He's A Latchico, 10/1 Activist, 14/1 Wewillgowithplanb,  Jiair Madrik, 50/1 Golden Move
column36: Faded into sixth on Irish/chasing debut at Naas, faces a huge task against his elders
column37: Winning hurdler in France at three; struggled in two Listed hurdle outings in March; faded into sixth at Naas on Irish/chasing debut; faces a huge task against his elders.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column36: Former top novice hurdler, chasing last term, could rebuild his reputation in this sphere
column37: Top novice hurdler the season before last with three Grade 1 wins; 2-5 over fences last season, no match for Sir Gino at Kempton; won Grade 1 at the DRF quite readily despite having raced keenly; flopped in the Brown Advisory won by stablemate Lecky Watson; more like it when second at Punchestown; every chance he can rebuild his reputation in this sphere.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column36: Highly dependable youngster, three wins and third in Galway Hurdle from last four starts
column37: Highly dependable youngster who has notched three wins and a third placing in the Galway Hurdle from his last four starts; accounted for the veteran Lord Erskine in a 2m handicap hurdle at Listowel; faced a straightforward task in a three-runner contest at Down Royal; this is ambitious.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column36: In fine shape since joining this stable, beat two rivals to take second in the Morgiana
column37: Signed off last season with a 2m6f handicap win at this venue; looked set for victory when dislodging his rider with a mistake at the last in a 2m Grade 3 event at Tipperary last month; gained quick compensation with an odds-on Punchestown win nine days later; did well to deprive the Galway Hurdle winner Ndaawi of second in the Morgiana Hurdle eight days ago.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column36: Recorded seventh hurdles win in a C&D Grade 2 in April, not in the same league as Teahupoo
column37: Recorded his seventh hurdles win when beating the Willie Mullins-trained Gala Marceau in a C&D Grade 2 in April; should be a bit sharper now following an outing in the Lismullen Hurdle at Navan; not in the same league as stablemate Teahupoo.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column32: John P McManus & Mrs John Magnier & Mrs S Ricci
column36: Brilliant two-mile novice two seasons ago, questions to answer after last season's lapses
column37: Second in the 2024 Supreme Novices' before 2m Grade 1 wins at Aintree and Punchestown; now has questions to answer after last season's failures in the Fighting Fifth, a 2m Grade 1 at Leopardstown and an ambitious Stayers' Hurdle bid.

column20: 11/4 Akimos,  Woodland Park, 7/2 John Barbour, 13/2 Ito Ditto, 8/1 Bolsover Bill, 14/1 My Bobby Dazzler,  Fresh Speculation, 20/1 Italian Spirit, 25/1 Woodythewoodpecker
column27: S C E A Haras Du Hoguenet Et Al
column36: Won this in 2022 and 2023, beaten by Lossiemouth last year, good chance he can make amends
column37: Caused a surprise when beating Klassical Dream in this race in 2022; following year, beat Impaire Et Passe here as prelude to a brilliant campaign in which he won Stayers' Hurdle and the Punchestown equivalent; no match for Lossiemouth 12 months ago; beaten by Bob Olinger at Cheltenham before signing off with Punchestown win; sets a very high standard.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Won the Irish Cesarewitch after second to Last Kingdom at Listowel, good 7lb claimer
column37: Last season's Fred Winter winner; landed the Irish Cesarewitch only three days after finishing second to Last Kingdom in the Lartigue at Listowel; good 7lb claimer gives him a serious chance.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Raised 8lb for beating Puturhandstogether at Listowel, could be close between the pair
column37: French AQPS winner; initially disappointing over hurdles when coming to Ireland; improved in the spring, winning a C&D novice handicap; later runner-up at Killarney and Ballinrobe; raised 8lb for beating Puturhandstogether at Listowel; could be close between the pair.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Useful 142-rated chaser, modest strike rate over fences, fair hurdler early in career
column37: Useful 142-rated chaser, modest strike rate over fences; fair hurdler early in career but might just be a bit ring-rusty when it comes to technique; has had a recent chase run.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Former smart juvenile hurdler, now on his second trainer since leaving Gavin Cromwell
column37: Former smart juvenile hurdler; now on his second trainer since leaving Gavin Cromwell for whom he was a Grade 2 C&D winner and second in a Grade 1 event Punchestown; visored now.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Kept good company over fences last season, made a pleasing return to hurdling at Galway
column37: Won a novice handicap at the 2023 Christmas fixture at Leopardstown; kept good company over fences last season; made a pleasing return to hurdling when third over 2m6f at Galway in October; has a fighting chance for a small local stable.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Better known as a five-time Flat winner, also effective over hurdles, worth a market check
column37: Recorded fifth win on the Flat when scoring at Galway in July despite stumbling badly (2m, soft); ran well over hurdles there three days later; disappointing on the Flat at Clonmel in September; more like it again when third at 50-1 in a 1m4f handicap at Leopardstown.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column27: Al Shira'Aa Farms S A R L
column36: Fifth to Puturhandstogether in the Fred Winter, Flat winner since unplaced at Listowel
column37: Turned into a decent juvenile hurdler last season, winning once and was fifth to Puturhandstogether in the Fred Winter; soundly beaten in seventh behind Last Kingdom in a handicap hurdle at Listowel; back to form when winning a 1m4f handicap on heavy ground at Galway last month.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: French import has come good with a handicap hurdle win and a Flat win (AW), big chance
column37: Dual-purpose type; ran in good company in maidens last season; won a Kilbeggan handicap hurdle in September (2m, gd-yld) off 8lb lower and with 7lb claimed; added to two Flat wins in France when scoring over 1m4f at Dundalk last month on his AW debut; won on soft on the Flat in France.

column20: 4/5 There Runs Mary, 2/1 Smart Decision, 7/1 Sir Hobnob, 20/1 My Fortune, 25/1 Eaststone Buck's, 50/1 Golden Prince
column36: Record of six seconds from ten starts over hurdles is off-putting, blinkers tried
column37: Looks capable of picking up a race but his record of six seconds from ten starts over hurdles is off-putting; fair run last time when third in a handicap at Navan; tried with blinkers for the first time and gets weight from all ten rivals.

column36: Fifth in this last year; creditable G1 third latest; may reward each-way support
column37: Most recent win came in the Grade 1 Spring Tenno Sho at Kyoto (2m, good) back in April 2023; finished fifth in last year's renewal of this (under Demuro) and it was a creditable effort when close third of 14 in the Grade 1 Autumn Tenno Sho (1m2f, good to firm) earlier this month; not quite the percentage call but may reward each-way support.

column36: Japanese Derby winner who was snookered by the draw in the Arc last time; big player
column37: Champion 2yo who was an odds-on second in the Grade 1 Japanese 2,000 Guineas before landing the Grade 1 Japanese Derby over C&D (good to firm) in June; soft ground didn't stop him winning the Group 3 Prix du Prince d'Orange at Longchamp in September before he was butchered by the draw in the Arc the following month; major player back on home shores.

column36: Beat two home in G1 here earlier this month and would be a shock winner
column37: Beat two home in the Grade 1 Autumn Tenno Sho here (1m2f, good to firm) earlier this month and would be a shock winner.

column36: Good effort to win G2 (1m4f, good) last month; still needs a big personal best to score
column37: Good effort to win the Grade 2 Kyoto Daishoten (1m4f, good) last month; had a few of these behind him that day but this is an altogether different test and he'll need a big personal best to score.

column36: Ran off with 1m7f G2 in March; solid return last month; might have a bit more to offer
column37: Ran off with the Grade 2 Hanshin Daishoten (1m7f, good to firm) in March and it was a solid return when second to Deep Monster in the Grade 2 Kyoto Daishoten (1m4f, good) last month; no surprise if he turns those tables today, with him likely having a bit more to offer.

column36: Could only beat one home back in Grade 1 company last time and needs to step up markedly
column37: Close-up sixth in the 2023 Japanese Derby over C&D (good to firm; 284-1) and won a Grade 3 handicap at Hakodate (1m2f, good to firm) in July 2024; second of 11 in the Grade 2 Mainichi Okan here (1m1f, good to firm) in October but could only beat one home back in Grade 1 company last time.

column36: Underwhelming comeback when beating three home in a G3 in August; leap of faith required
column37: Sixth and ninth in the last two renewals of this; good third of 16 in the Dubai Turf at Meydan (1m1f, good) in between but it was an underwhelming comeback when beating three home in a Niigata Grade 3 (1m2f, good to firm) in late August; leap of faith required.

column27: Haras De Son Altesse L'Aga Khan Scea
column36: Currently rated the world's best racehorse and he's on a G1 four-timer; leading claims
column37: Last seven starts all Group 1s; found Danon Decile too good in the Sheema Classic at Meydan (1m4f, good) in April but that came during a run of seconds and he's turned a corner since, winning the Grand Prix de Saint-Cloud (good to soft) in June, the King George (also 1m4f, good) in July and the Champion Stakes (Ascot again, 1m2f, good) last month; particularly impressive in the latter event and holds solid claims of wrestling this prize away from the locals for the first time since 2005.

column36: Yet to win above G3 level; mid-division in G1 (1m2f, good to firm) last time; passed over
column37: Yet to win above Grade 3 level and was only mid-division in the Grade 1 Autumn Tenno Sho here (1m2f, good to firm) last time; passed over.

column36: Won two G2s in spring of 2024; hasn't matched that since
column37: Won two Grade 2s in the spring of 2024 but hasn't matched that since and was beaten in a Grade 2 handicap over C&D last time.

column36: Won G2 handicap over C&D in June; encouraging return last month; could well build on that
column37: Third in last year's Japanese St Leger at Kyoto (1m7f, good to firm); narrowly won a Grade 2 handicap over C&D in June and was a well-supported favourite when fourth to Deep Monster on his comeback in the Grade 2 Kyoto Daishoten (1m4f, good) last month; could well build on that.

column36: Capable 7yo but 0-5 in G1s and would need a career best to take this, which seems unlikely
column37: Capable 7yo but he's 0-5 in Group 1s and would need a career best to take this, which seems unlikely.

column36: The sole mare; won 1m3f G1 two years ago and G2 here last October; quieter since
column37: The sole mare; won Grade 1 Queen Elizabeth II Cup at Kyoto (1m3f, good to firm) two years ago and came back from a 337-day break to land a Grade 2 here (1m1f, good to firm) last October; hasn't matched that since, however, and this is a tough race to stage the revival.

column36: Beat Calandagan in Meydan G1 in April; latest effort best ignored; contender
column37: 2024 Japanese Derby winner who beat Calandagan in the Group 1 Sheema Classic at Meydan (1m4f, good) in April; flopped when just 7-2 in the International at York (10.5f, good to firm) in August but that's probably a run to put a line through; much respected back on home soil.

column36: Career best when winning G1 here (1m2f, also good to firm) this month; big player
column37: Chased home Croix Du Nord in the Japanese Derby over C&D in June and it was a career best when winning the Autumn Tenno Sho here (1m2f, also good to firm) under Lemaire at the start of the month; improving 3yo who commands serious respect.

column36: Big run in this last year; won G2 in February; has the talent to get involved
column37: Well-travelled colt who dead-heated for second in this race last year; won a Group 2 at Riyadh (10.5f, good to firm) in February but way below that in two Group 1s subsequently; has the talent to get involved but others look more solid.

column36: Shared 2nd in this last year; good effort on next start but not matched since; may revive
column37: Dead-heated for second in this race last year; good effort on his next start when third to Danon Decile and Calandagan in the Group 1 Sheema Classic at Meydan (1m4f, good) in April but the wheels have come off in two subsequent starts, latterly behind Deep Monster in the Grade 2 Kyoto Daishoten (1m4f, good) last month; needs a revival, which isn't out of the question.

column36: Doubled G1 tally (1m2f, good) in April; excuses on return this month; far from discounted
column37: Good second of 15 in the Autumn Tenno Sho here (good to firm) last October and he doubled his Group 1 tally when landing the QEII Cup at Sha Tin (also 1m2f, good) in April; had excuses when mid-division behind Masquerade Ball on his return earlier in the month and he's far from discounted.
